INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '58cc2da2-706e-4722-bb26-80ffb4d1c706',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$CSS Modules — Why They Win the Styling Strategy Debate for Component-Heavy UIs$escape$,
  $escape$CSS Modules occupy a precise sweet spot: scoped styles without a runtime cost. Every class you write gets transformed into a unique identifier at build time — `.button` becomes `_button_1a2b3_1` — so collisions are structurally impossible without any naming convention overhead like BEM.

Unlike utility-first (Tailwind), CSS Modules keep styling concerns in `.module.css` files, leaving JSX readable. Unlike CSS-in-JS (styled-components, Emotion), there's zero runtime style injection, no hydration mismatch risk, and no bundle overhead from a styling library.

The `composes` keyword is underused but powerful: it lets you inherit styles from another class within the same file or across modules using `composes: base from './base.module.css'`. This enables a lean design-token layer without a full utility framework.

Local scope is opt-out via `:global(.className)` when you genuinely need global reach — think third-party widget overrides. The default is safe; global is explicit. For teams shipping component libraries or co-located feature slices, CSS Modules provide the right level of isolation with no tradeoffs on performance.$escape$,
  $escape$/* button.module.css */
.base {
  padding: 0.5rem 1rem;
  border-radius: 4px;
  font-weight: 600;
}

.primary {
  composes: base;
  background: var(--color-brand);
  color: #fff;
}

/* Override a third-party tooltip globally */
:global(.tippy-box) {
  font-size: 0.75rem;
}

// Button.tsx
import styles from './button.module.css';
export const Button = () => <button className={styles.primary}>Submit</button>;$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
