INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '7563476e-7925-4fe2-98f2-ebb183ef850c',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$CSS Modules + cva — Type-Safe Component Variants Without Tailwind$escape$,
  $escape$CSS Modules give you scoped class names, but managing variant combinations manually — `${styles.btn} ${size === 'sm' ? styles.sm : styles.lg} ${disabled ? styles.disabled : ''}` — becomes unmaintainable fast. `cva` (class-variance-authority) solves this cleanly, and it's not a Tailwind-only tool.

Pass your CSS Module class references directly as variant values. `cva` accepts any string, including the hashed identifiers your module exports. Define a `base` class for shared styles, declare `variants` keyed to your module's size/intent/state classes, and use `compoundVariants` for combinations — like `size: 'lg'` + `intent: 'danger'` — that require their own dedicated class.

The returned function is fully typed. TypeScript errors on invalid variant values, and `VariantProps<typeof button>` derives your component's prop types directly from the variant map — your `.module.css` file stays the single source of truth.

For theming, map variant keys to CSS custom-property classes (`.themeLight`, `.themeDark`) rather than inlining `var()` calls in JS. Cascade logic belongs in the stylesheet, not scattered across variant definitions.$escape$,
  $escape$import { cva, type VariantProps } from 'class-variance-authority';
import styles from './Button.module.css';

const button = cva(styles.base, {
  variants: {
    size: { sm: styles.sm, md: styles.md, lg: styles.lg },
    intent: { primary: styles.primary, danger: styles.danger },
  },
  compoundVariants: [
    { size: 'lg', intent: 'danger', class: styles.lgDanger },
  ],
  defaultVariants: { size: 'md', intent: 'primary' },
});

type ButtonProps = VariantProps<typeof button> & React.ButtonHTMLAttributes<HTMLButtonElement>;

export function Button({ size, intent, className, ...props }: ButtonProps) {
  return <button className={button({ size, intent, className })} {...props} />;
}$escape$,
