INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'b8c1126e-9bb7-4550-ad66-6b1c47f5649f',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$CSS Modules Dark Mode — :global, prefers-color-scheme, and Killing the Flash$escape$,
  $escape$CSS Modules scope class names, not custom properties — variables live in the cascade and are inherently global. To define theme tokens inside a module file, use :global to hoist them onto :root or a [data-theme] attribute. Any component module can then consume var(--color-bg) directly with no import chain, because custom properties pierce the scoping boundary.

For system preference, add a @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) block targeting :global(:root:not([data-theme])). This fires only when no explicit override is set, so user-toggled themes always win.

The flash-on-load problem is a JS concern, not a CSS one. A blocking inline <script> in <head> — executing before the first paint — reads localStorage and sets document.documentElement.dataset.theme synchronously. Never use useEffect for this: it fires after hydration, after the browser has already painted the default theme. In Next.js App Router, inject the script via dangerouslySetInnerHTML in layout.tsx or use next/script with strategy="beforeInteractive". Alternatively, read a cookie server-side and pass data-theme to <html> as a prop — zero client JS needed.$escape$,
  $escape$// app/layout.tsx — blocks paint until theme is resolved
const setTheme = `(function(){
  const t = localStorage.getItem('theme');
  const dark = matchMedia('(prefers-color-scheme: dark)').matches;
  document.documentElement.dataset.theme = t ?? (dark ? 'dark' : 'light');
})()`;$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
