INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'feb2bc79-8043-4240-a255-83f5bd7c86da',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$CSS Modules — Runtime Theming with CSS Custom Properties and JavaScript Interop$escape$,
  $escape$CSS Modules scopes class names at build time, but CSS custom properties (variables) pierce that encapsulation intentionally — they cascade and are readable/writable at runtime. This gives you a clean seam for JavaScript interop without breaking the module boundary.

Define your theme tokens inside a `:local` scoped selector or directly on `:root` via a global import. Within a CSS Module, reference custom properties normally — they resolve at runtime, not compile time, so the module hash doesn't affect them.

To scope a theme to a single component, set the custom properties on the component's root element via `style` prop in React. The composes keyword won't help here — that's static. Instead, pass a CSSProperties object with your `--var` overrides. Child elements in the same module that reference those variables will pick them up through normal cascade, fully contained within that DOM subtree.

Avoid setting custom properties in the CSS Module file itself for dynamic values — that's a build-time artifact. Keep dynamic values in inline styles on the host element; keep structural rules in the module.$escape$,
  $escape$// Button.module.css
.button {
  background: var(--btn-bg, #0070f3);
  color: var(--btn-text, #fff);
  padding: 0.5rem 1rem;
  border-radius: 4px;
}

// Button.tsx
import styles from './Button.module.css';

type Props = { bg?: string; text?: string; label: string };

export function Button({ bg, text, label }: Props) {
  return (
    <button
      className={styles.button}
      style={{ '--btn-bg': bg, '--btn-text': text } as React.CSSProperties}
    >
      {label}
    </button>
  );
}$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
