INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '2c025a30-3a51-4657-bea1-027b672a34f9',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$CSS Modules Performance — Critical CSS, Layout Thrash, and When will-change Backfires$escape$,
  $escape$CSS Modules adds per-component stylesheets lazily — every `import styles from './Foo.module.css'` ships a separate chunk. For above-the-fold components, extract critical selectors into a single `critical.module.css` imported at the app entry point and keep component modules for the rest. This eliminates FOUC without inflating your initial payload.

Layout thrash occurs when JS alternates DOM reads and writes. CSS Modules won't prevent it, but `composes` lets you batch visual state into a single class swap — one reflow instead of multiple `element.style.*` mutations. Toggle `styles.active` rather than setting `opacity`, `transform`, and `top` individually in JS.

`will-change: transform` in a module promotes that element to its own compositor layer — correct for a transient `.animating` class, dangerous on `.container`. Layer cost is per-instance; in a list of 200 cards, a persistent `will-change` on each card root saturates GPU memory. Instead, compose `will-change` into a short-lived `.cardLifted` class, apply it on `pointerdown`, and remove it on `animationend`. CSS Modules' local scoping guarantees this class stays component-contained and never leaks into sibling trees.$escape$,
  $escape$// Card.module.css
// .card { border-radius: 8px; transition: transform 200ms ease; }
// .cardLifted { composes: card; will-change: transform; }

import styles from './Card.module.css';
import { useState } from 'react';

export function Card({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  const [lifted, setLifted] = useState(false);
  return (
    <div
      className={lifted ? styles.cardLifted : styles.card}
      onPointerDown={() => setLifted(true)}
      onAnimationEnd={() => setLifted(false)}
    >
      {children}
    </div>
  );
}$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
