INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '6311985c-15de-4d05-8c5a-8e0b0374e3a6',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$CSS Modules — Linting, Formatting, and a Tight PostCSS Pipeline$escape$,
  $escape$Without guardrails, CSS Modules projects drift fast — inconsistent class naming, unscoped globals sneaking in, and composes chains that break silently. Lock it down with three tools wired together.

Stylelint catches the module-specific problems. Use stylelint-config-css-modules alongside the standard config to suppress false positives on :local and :global pseudo-selectors, and add the selector-class-pattern rule set to kebab-case to enforce consistent .my-component naming across every .module.css file.

Prettier handles formatting — wire it through stylelint-prettier so a single stylelint --fix pass both formats and lints. No separate prettier --write step needed.

PostCSS sits upstream in the build. Order matters: run postcss-import first so composes: … from './tokens.module.css' resolves before CSS Modules scoping runs, then autoprefixer, then your CSS Modules transform. Misconfigured order is the most common reason composes silently outputs the base class name but drops the composed styles at runtime.

Add a lint-staged hook scoped to **/*.module.css so none of this runs on global stylesheets — you want different rules there.$escape$,
  $escape$// .stylelintrc.json
{
  "extends": [
    "stylelint-config-standard",
    "stylelint-config-css-modules",
    "stylelint-prettier/recommended"
  ],
  "rules": {
    "selector-class-pattern": "^[a-z][a-zA-Z0-9]+$",
    "selector-pseudo-class-no-unknown": [true, {
      "ignorePseudoClasses": ["local", "global"]
    }]
  }
}

// postcss.config.js — order is load-bearing
module.exports = {
  plugins: [
    require('postcss-import'),
    require('autoprefixer'),
    // css-modules transform applied by bundler after this chain
  ]
}$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
