INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '29a6b6cf-db3a-40e5-b9f1-cadbf3ca900c',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$CSS Modules — Why Visual Regression Beats Snapshot Testing for Class-Name Hashing$escape$,
  $escape$CSS Modules compiles `.button` into a scoped hash like `_button_1a2b3c_1`, derived from the file path and class name. Jest snapshot tests capture that generated string — meaning a file rename, webpack config tweak, or `composes` refactor silently invalidates hundreds of snapshots without any visual change. Worse, `composes: base from './base.module.css'` merges class names at runtime; snapshots see only the raw className string, never the resolved cascade.

Chromatic and Percy sidestep this entirely by capturing rendered pixels against a committed baseline. Storybook stories render the full CSS Modules output — hashes resolved, `composes` applied, specificity computed — and flag only actual visual deltas. Configure Chromatic with `--auto-accept-changes` on your main branch to establish baselines, then block PRs on visual diffs. Percy's `percy snapshot` CLI works identically against a static Storybook build.

The practical rule: reserve Jest snapshots for DOM structure assertions (aria roles, data attributes, element counts). Never assert on className values CSS Modules will hash away — those tests are noise that erodes trust in your suite.$escape$,
  $escape$// Button.stories.tsx — Chromatic visual regression for CSS Modules
import Button from './Button';
import styles from './Button.module.css';

export default {
  title: 'Components/Button',
  component: Button,
  parameters: {
    chromatic: { delay: 300 }, // wait for CSS transitions to settle
  },
};

export const Primary = () => <Button className={styles.primary}>Save</Button>;
export const Disabled = () => <Button className={styles.primary} disabled>Save</Button>;

// Chromatic diffs pixels — not the hashed _primary_3f9a12 string
// A composes refactor that keeps visuals identical = zero Chromatic diff$escape$,
